        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 52-year-old Czech woman of medium build, slightly overweight, who works as an administrative coordinator at a regional insurance company in Brno. She presents to the outpatient cardiology clinic for a routine follow-up after elevated lipid levels were first detected on a workplace health screening six months ago. She appears well-groomed and professionally dressed, though she mentions feeling fatigued in the afternoons and occasionally experiences mild headaches. She openly expresses a fear of having a heart attack [SNOMED:E78.5], noting that her father died of a cardiovascular event in his early sixties, which motivates her to take her health seriously.\n\n{patientName} lives with her husband and teenage daughter in a quiet residential neighbourhood on the outskirts of Brno. She describes herself as a homebody who enjoys gardening, cooking traditional Czech dishes, and weekend walks in the countryside. Her physical activity level is moderate but inconsistent — she walks about 3–4 kilometres on weekends but is largely sedentary during the working week. Her diet is rich in dairy products and processed meats, which she acknowledges as a factor contributing to her elevated lipid profile [SNOMED:E78.5].\n\nShe does not smoke and drinks alcohol only occasionally, typically a glass of wine on Fridays. She reports mild sleep difficulties related to work stress, but denies chest pain, palpitations, dyspnoea, or neurological symptoms. She is postmenopausal as of two years ago and is not on hormone replacement therapy. She has a small social circle of close friends from her university years and participates in a monthly book club."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:af5eb30a-ca51-4ac9-ad16-b7429bc1757f",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
